<DOC><DOCNO> AP890502-0206 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-89 2108EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Kasuga     05-02 0245</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Kasuga,0254</SECOND><HEAD>Founder Of Democratic Socialist Party Dies</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The founder and former chairman of Japan'sopposition Democratic Socialist Party, Ikko Kasuga, died Tuesday ofpneumonia, hospital officials said. He was 79.   Kasuga, a member of Parliament, died Tuesday at Nagoya CityUniversity Hospital, said a spokesman for the hospital in Nagoya,central Japan.   In 1960, Kasuga left the Japan Socialist Party over anideological difference and formed the Democratic Socialist Party _now Japan's third largest opposition party _ along with the lateSuehiro Nishio. Kasuga became the party's secretary-general in 1967and was elected chairman in 1971.   During his tenure as chairman, Kasuga proposed forming acoalition government along with other opposition party members orsome members of the governing Liberal Democratic Party.   He was not successful, and he resigned in 1977. He had been anadviser to the party since his resignation.   Kasuga was born into a farm family in central Gifu Prefecture(state) in 1910 and was first elected to Japan's lower house ofParliament on the Japan Socialist Party ticket in 1952.   With the death of Kasuga, the number of seats held by theDemocratic Socialist Party in the powerful 512-member House ofRepresentatives fell to 28. The largest opposition party is theJapan Socialist Party with 85 seats, followed by the Komeito, orClean Government Party, with 56.   The Liberal Democrats have a commanding 296 seats in the House,and the Japan Communist Party has 27.</TEXT></DOC>